<HEAD>
<TITLE>CPJ Dangerous Assignments Quarterly</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER><!-- Graphic Tag --><IMG WIDTH=450 HEIGHT=101 BORDER=0 ALT="Dangerous Assignments Quarterly" SRC="../../../pictures/newsletter.gif"></CENTER>


<hr>
<table width=100%>
<!-- Font Tag --><td><FONT SIZE=2>Fall 1995<td align=center><FONT SIZE=2>Internet Edition<td align=right><FONT SIZE=2>No. 49</tr></FONT>
</table>
<hr>



<!-- Graphic Tag --><IMG WIDTH=125		 HEIGHT=125 VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 align=right BORDER=1  SRC="rohde.jpeg"><br><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=2><!-- Font Tag -->Photograph of David Rohde.<I> AP photo.</I></FONT><br>
<br>
<hr>

<h2> Bosnian Serbs release U.S. journalist<br> after CPJ intervenes <br>
<!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=3></FONT></h2>
By Jeanne Sahadi<br>
<br>

Taking journalists hostage has become a tactic of the Bosnian Serbs, who often use their captives to secure the release of their own POWs. <P>

<I> Christian Science Monitor</I> reporter David Rohde, however, was the first journalist to be charged and convicted of crimes in retaliation for his reporting on Bosnian Serb atrocities. He helped expose the massacre of thousands of Muslims by Bosnian Serb forces after their capture of Srebrenica.<P>

 During his illegal detention, which began on Oct. 29, Rohde was tried and convicted of illegally entering Bosnian Serb territory and of falsifying documents. <P>

 Three meetings between CPJ Chair Kati Marton and Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic at the Dayton, Ohio, peace talks helped secure Rohde&#146;s release on Nov. 8. &#147In my meetings with Mr. Milosevic, I made it clear to him that the American media would not let go of the David Rohde story until he was safe and free,&#148; Marton said. &#147I urged him to work with his Bosnian Serb colleagues to bring this situation to a positive end.&#148;<P>

 Upon his release, Rohde was cleared of all charges as &#147a sign of goodwill and contribution&#148; to the talks, according to Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic.<P>

 Acknowledging the cooperative effort that secured Rohde&#146;s freedom, J. Anthony Periton, editor in chief of The Christian Science Publishing Society, said, &#147This outcome would not have been possible without the help of a large group of people. We particularly want to thank the U.S. State Department, the United Nations,  the International Committee of the Red Cross and the Committee to Protect Journalists.&#148;<BR>


<br>
<hr>
<table width=100%>
<tr>
<td>
<font size=2>
(c) 1996 Committee Protect Journalists
</font> 
</td>
<td align=right valign=top widthto Protect Journalists
</font> 
</td>
<td align=right valign=top width=50%>
<font size=2>
| <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="49index.html">Front Page</A>
| <a href="http://www.cpj.org/">CPJ Website</a> |
</font>
</td>
</tr>
