<STRONG>Gao Yu<BR>
</STRONG>
<CITE>Imprisoned: </CITE>
October 2, 1993<BR>
Two days before she was to depart for the United States to start a one-year research 
fellowship at Columbia University's Graduate School of Journalism, Gao, a free-lance 
journalist, was detained on Oct. 2, 1993. On Nov. 10, 1994, she was tried without 
counsel and sentenced to six years in prison for "leaking state secrets" about China's 
structural reforms in articles for the pro-Beijing Hong Kong magazine Mirror Monthly. 
Gao was previously jailed for 14 months following the June 1989 Tiananmen Square 
demonstrations and released in August 1990 after showing symptoms of a heart condition.<BR>
