<h2>Reporting ugly truths in Russia<br>
<!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=3>CPJ honors Yevgeny Kiselyov</FONT></h2>
By Jeanne Sahadi<br>
<br>
The Russian government&#146;s efforts to control coverage of the Chechen conflict were, in the end, futile. Public opinion turned against Boris Yeltsin, and he found himself fighting not only to put down a rebellion but to salvage his political career.<BR>
<br>


<!-- Graphic Tag --><IMG WIDTH=225 HEIGHT=150 VSPACE=10 BORDER=1 ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="russia.jpg"><br><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=2><!-- Font Tag --> Russian prisoners of war in Chechnya. At the risk of losing its license, Russia&#146;s first editorially and financially independent network, NTV, showed the stark realities of the Chechen conflict. <I>AP photo.</I></FONT><br>
</table>
<!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="russia.html">FULL STORY</A>
<br><hr><br>

<ul>
<li><B><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="pioneers.html">Pioneers and patriots</A></B><BR>
CPJ&#146;s executive director examines journalists&#146; role in nation-building<P>

<li><B><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="marcus.html">U.S. reporter acquitted in Turkey</A></B><BR>
Aliza Marcus case draws international attention<P>

<li><B><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="rohde.html">Bosnian Serbs release U.S. journalist</A></B><br>
David Rohde set free during peace talks<P>

<li><B><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="ghezali.html">Algerian editor speaks out</A></B><BR>
Selima Ghezali of <I>La Nation</I><P>

<li><B><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="bradlee.html">Ben Bradlee: Stories from a good life in journalism</A></B><BR>
Excerpts from the memoirs of CPJ's 1995 Burton Benjamin Memorial Award honoree<P>

<li><B><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="world.html">Around the world</A></B><BR>
Briefs on Jordan, Kashmir, Sierra Leone, Brazil, The Gambia, Yemen, Cuba and Cambodia<P>

<li><B><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="satter.html">Deadly silence in Tajikistan</A></B><BR>
CPJ revisits Central Asia<p>

<li><B><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="yuenger.html">New Fund in Memory of James Yuenger</A></B><BR><p>

<li><B><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="homophobic.html">Homophobic Attacks on the Press</A></B><BR>
New report on press freedom violations on gay and lesbian journalists<p>
</ul>
<hr>
<font size=2><I>Dangerous Assignments</I> is published quarterly by the Committee to Protect Journalists, a nonpartisan, nonprofit organization founded in 1981 to monitor and promote freedom of the press around the world.<p>
News services provided by Agence France-Presse, Associated Press, <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.lexis-nexis.com/">LEXIS-NEXIS</A> and <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.reuters.com/index.html">Reuters</A> America, Inc.<p>

