<HEAD>
<TITLE>CPJ Dangerous Assignments Quarterly</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER><!-- Graphic Tag --><IMG WIDTH=450 HEIGHT=101 BORDER=0 ALT="Dangerous Assignments Quarterly" SRC="../../../pictures/newsletter.gif"></CENTER>


<hr>
<table width=100%>
<!-- Font Tag --><td><FONT SIZE=2>Fall 1995<td align=center><FONT SIZE=2>Internet Edition<td align=right><FONT SIZE=2>No. 49</tr></FONT>
</table>
<hr>

<!-- Graphic Tag --><IMG WIDTH=225 HEIGHT=150 align=right BORDER=1 vspace=10  hspace =10 SRC="marcus.jpeg"><br>
<font size=2> CPJ Honorary Chair Walter Cronkite met with Turkish Prime Minister Tansu Ciller in Ankara in September to urge the dismissal of charges against Reuters correspondent Aliza Marcus.<I>
Photo by Michael Adler.</I></FONT><br><BR>
<hr>

<h2>Reuters reporter targeted in Turkey&#146;s censorship campaign<BR>
<!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=3></FONT></h2>
By Jeanne Sahadi<br><BR>



U.S. reporter Aliza Marcus, the Istanbul correspondent for Reuters, thought she was simply doing her job when she reported on the forced evacuation of Kurdish villages in November 1994. <P>

Turkish authorities thought differently. Her story, which appeared in the Kurdish paper <CITE>&Ouml;zg&uuml;r &Uuml;lke</CITE>, caught their attention. In July 1995, well past the six-month statute of limitations under which formal charges may be brought, they charged Marcus with &#147inciting racial hatred&#148; under Article 312 of the Penal Code, a provision frequently used to quell open discussion of the Kurds. Those convicted face up to three years in jail. <P>

Fortunately for Marcus, who is the first American to become ensnared by this censorship campaign, Istanbul&#146;s State Security Court acquitted her of all charges on Nov. 9. But not before the reporter waged a time-consuming legal battle, and CPJ spearheaded an international campaign on her behalf.<P>

In addition to sending protest letters, arranging editorial board meetings between Marcus and the press, and lobbying influential U.S. congressmen to urge Turkish authorities to drop the charges against her, CPJ went straight to Turkey&#146;s prime minister.<P>

Walter Cronkite, CPJ&#146;s honorary chair, met with Tansu Ciller in Ankara in September. &#147As I explained to the prime minister, Turkey&#146;s international image as a democratic nation would have been badly battered if the prosecution of Ms. Marcus moved forward,&#148; Cronkite said.<P>

That image is one Ciller has been eager to maintain as the country is anxiously seeking membership in the European customs union.<P>

In October, the Turkish parliament voted to reduce the penalties called for under Article 8, a part of the country&#146;s anti-terror law that broadly defines &#147separatist propaganda,&#148; a charge that has been used frequently to jail journalists writing about the Kurds. At the end of 1994, CPJ documented the imprisonment of 74 journalists in Turkey--more than any other country in the world. <P>

Ciller said the changes to Article 8 &#147will help insure that Turkey&#146;s citizens enjoy full freedom of expression, along with safeguards against terrorism.&#148; Short of throwing out Article 8 and Article 312 altogether, however, any such incremental changes are inadequate to bring about real improvement in the treatment of the press in Turkey.<P>

After she was acquitted, Marcus said: &#147I was really happy to see all the support I got from CPJ and other groups. I hadn&#146;t realized how much pressure I had been feeling. Now I look forward to getting back to work without having to worry about this case.&#148; <BR>

	
<br>

